The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, July 14: State-owned oil marketing firms IOC, BPCL and HPCL today decided to have a uniform petrol price despite the government giving them the freedom to price the fuel. The three retailers will coordinate once in a month on the pricing of petrol based on the international price trend of crude oil and gasoline, IOC director (finance) S.V. Narasimhan said.                             
	 New Delhi, July 14: Reliance Industries has moved the Competition Commission of India, alleging oil firms IOC, BPCL and HPCL have formed a cartel to supply aviation turbine fuel to Air India. It is learnt that RIL wants to enter the business of jet fuel supply, which is in the hands state-owned oil marketing companies.                            
	 New Delhi, July 14: The government will endeavour to bring in an FDI policy on multi-brand retail by October but the final call rests with the political leadership, R.P. Singh, secretary in the department of industrial policy and promotion, said today.                             
	 Mumbai, July 14: Income tax officers and staff across the country will observe a token strike tomorrow to press their demands, which include putting an end to outsourcing of departmental functions at the central processing centre in Bangalore.                             
	 New Delhi, July 14: The State Bank of India and the State General Reserve Fund of Oman have agreed to form a joint investment fund. The fund will start with a corpus of $100 million to make equity investments in various sectors of the Indian economy.                             
	 New Delhi, July 14: The government will infuse Rs 111 crore into the Union Bank of India as part of its planned capital support to the state-run banks to shore up their lending capacity.                            
	 Hyderabad, July 14: Larsen amp; Toubro has emerged as the lowest bidder for the Rs 12,132-crore Hyderabad metro project.
                                                                                                                          
